english:
  title: Preface to the Commentary on the Avatamsaka Sutra in the Jin Translation
  author: Won Hyo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the beginning, the Dharma-realm without obstruction, without impediment—this gateway of the Dharma—is law yet no law, gate yet no gate. Thus it is neither great nor small, neither deficient nor excessive, neither moving nor still, neither one nor many. Because it is not great, it fashions the infinitesimal and leaves nothing behind. Because it is not small, it becomes the vastness and still has remainder. Because it is not deficient, it embraces the three times and all their kalpas. Because it is not excessive, the whole enters into a single realm. Neither moving nor still, death-and-birth becomes Nirvana, and Nirvana becomes death-and-birth. Neither one nor many, one dharma is all dharmas, and all dharmas are one dharma.

    Such is the dharma without obstruction, without impediment—the art of the Dharma-realm gateway. This is where great bodhisattvas enter, whence the Buddhas of three times emerge. It is what the two vehicles and four fruits remain deaf and blind to, what common beings and lower folk laugh at in wonder. Yet if one gains entry to this gateway, in a single thought one transcends, and all three times manifest boundlessly. The ten-direction worlds compress into a single grain of dust. Such mysteries—how could they be conceived?

    Yet when viewed through that gateway, this matter is merely stepping outside the door thrice in a day while ten persons sit together in the hall—what wonder dwells in such a dry place? How much more so when Mount Sumeru enters a mustard seed, when rice enters the great granary, when a room-space enters the assembly, when the universe enters all things? The path of entry is vast—what difficulty remains?

    When the phoenix soars through azure clouds, the mountains appear lowly beneath. When the River Lord reaches the great ocean, he finds the streams ashamed in their narrowness. Thus the scholar entering the universal gateway of this sutra will finally recognize how constrained was former learning. Yet the short-winged bird shelters in forest to nurture its form, the tiny fish hides in the stream to settle its nature. Therefore, the shallow teachings are not without their necessity.

    This sutra is perfection itself, the supreme sudden teaching of the Dharma-wheel. It opens widely the gateway of the Dharma-realm, reveals the boundless virtues of practice. These virtues, though impartial, offer steps by which one may ascend. These steps make cultivation possible. This gateway, though without boundary, opens clear paths by which one may advance. Those who enter that gateway find nothing to enter, yet leave nothing un-entered. Those who cultivate these virtues gain nothing, yet leave nothing un-gained.

    Thus the three worthy and ten sage levels complete every practice. The three bodies and ten Buddhas perfect every virtue. Its words gleam with brilliance, its meanings flow without limit—how could they be fully praised?

    The great, expansive, adorned by Buddha—the Dharma-realm boundless makes it great and expansive; the virtues of practice without bias make it Buddha-adorned. Without greatness and expansion, Buddha cannot adorn it. Without Buddha's adornment, greatness cannot be perfected. Thus we speak of both expansion and adornment, marking the essence of vastness and perfection.

    The sutra is complete—the Dharma-wheel resonates through all directions, world-pervading, three times without partiality, reaching ultimate principle and exhausting the eternal. Therefore it is called a sutra. Taking this essential meaning as our mark, we proclaim it: the Great, Expansive Sutra of Buddha-Adornment.
  footnotes:
    - 'Four Fruits (四果): The four stages of attainment in the Theravada path—referring to stream-enterer, once-returner, non-returner, and arhat.'
    - 'The ''gateway'' metaphor pervades this passage, establishing a paradox central to Huayan philosophy: entry is both necessary and illusory, movement both required and non-existent.'
